Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his company. Quietly, he got up from his cot, put on his combat suit, threw on his body armor, and took his things out of the locker, being careful with a certain small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Hanging there was everything he needed, like his respirator or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition belts, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before opening the door a little. In the last week, he had to come up with all sorts of ideas to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm, because it usually didn't work and only produced a faint noise from the speakers.
“Are you waking them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemic approaching him.
“Yes,” answered Cohren.
“What are you going to try this time?”
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others were already approaching him in full gear.
“Good morning,” said Craith.
“What woke you up, then?” asked Cohren.
“Well, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you would come up with today. And secondly, the assault troops, who are the first to get up, get to choose their morning ration,” replied one of the men, Ravik. “And you know how bad the food can be.”
“Good argument, Corporal,” said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a button. A loud, shrill alarm echoed through the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled cursing and people running around in a panic.
“Man, Valturi,” said Nemic. “One would think they would have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you.”
“Well, my people from the training camp have learned it,” replied Cohren, pointing to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. “However, the platoon and company leaders also know that they have to get up before their units.”
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others more annoyed.
“Good morning,” said Cohren in a good mood.
“With all due respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?” asked a corporal from the assault team.
“Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn’t want to sleep through it,” said Cohren.
“Pack all your personal items,” Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and acting officer of the company, he was responsible for supervising and supporting them along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. “We are not coming back here. Corporals and lieutenants, you and your platoons have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations.”
The members of the Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the second assault division, second army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid being detected by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
“A new day and a new mission for the hellhounds,” Nemic said with a dry laugh. “Where are they sending us?”
“A forward operating base outside Ianlos. We will support the ground attack,” Cohren answered and took a puff on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for starting him smoking, but a year in the field changed a person, so he said nothing.
“Shit. It's getting worse at the front,” Nemic muttered. “All the news says: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' How about help for the Howland front?”
“Amen, brother,” Cohren said and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. “At least we're going out with the first armed platoon and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there.”
“Did Shaw arrange for us to ride along?” Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
“Yes. He’s honestly not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can tolerate him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put on his backpack. “All units of the Exodus Company will gather at West Parking Lot once they are ready. We will depart with the first armed platoon at 0500.”
He received instant responses from the platoon leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt like he had known them forever, even though it had been at most two years. They were platoon leaders, although Craith had been leading the second platoon for a week, after its previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the parking lot, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored personnel carriers. Their crews were running around, ensuring their machines were ready for deployment. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armed platoon. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them, as always with an expressionless face.
“Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valturi…” He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren’s pistol holster and then looked up again. “Is the company ready, I assume?”
